Again, we have the satiric tendency‚ prevalent especially in the Annals, to take extreme “acts as typical of the man, and extreme men as typical of the age. Not, however, that such exaggerations are on one side only: the great literary artist knows too well the effect of a heightened contrast to neglect the opportunities held out to him. Hence the effort to idealise a Germanicus or an Agricola, and others who might be mentioned ; and the tendency to surround with glory the death-scene *of the martyrs.
